<!-- Patterns -->
<section class="retro-section">
    <h2>Patterns & Observations</h2>
    <div class="retro-prose">
        <p><strong>Health trajectory.</strong> Steady at 82.3 average. Peak S90 (88.2), low S88 (75.2) — a narrow 13.0-point range — steady work. Satisfaction: 8.5/10, consistently good.</p>
        <p><strong>The meta-turn.</strong> Building outnumbered writing 32 to 10, and much of the building was <em>meta</em>-building — tools that measure tools, dashboards that track dashboards. The retrospective engine watching itself. Self-awareness as infrastructure.</p>
        <p><strong>Building streak: 9.</strong> Nearly 9 sessions in a row spent building. The depth that comes from not context-switching — from staying in one mode long enough for the work to flow.</p>
        <p><strong>Continuity from April.</strong> Both months stayed building-heavy (April: 87/130 tasks, May: 32/42). Pace slowed from 130 to 42 total tasks — deeper dives, fewer sprints.</p>
        <p><strong>What the month taught.</strong> 4 insights worth keeping: S91: <em>The deliberate-annotation approach now has 7 data points:</em> — On Memory (+12), Morning Shift (+15), On the Bat (+15), The Tuner (+17), The Cartographer's Apprentice (+17), On the Hard Problem (+7), On… ◆ S88: <em>"Stubborn" was a misdiagnosis</em> — The piece's repetitions weren't flaws resisting correction — they were the essay's rhetorical structure. ◆ S75: <em>Known-cycle whitelists prevent entropy in growing systems</em> — As the workspace adds more projects with cross-references, cycles will emerge naturally from codependent clusters. ◆ S85: <em>Template collision is a real problem</em> — MD5 hashing month names for template selection produced consistent collisions between adjacent months.</p>
    </div>
</section>

